english:
  title: Record on the Hall of Sincere Faith
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My colleague, Chamberlain Han, bears the title 'Hall of Sincere Faith,' its plaque inscribed by the visiting Chinese envoy Master Duanmu in clerical script, accompanied by a detailed account. He showed me this work and asked me to compose a record. As Chamberlain is a kinsman of our ancestral house and has long been my trusted friend and colleague, I cannot in conscience decline.

    A person's nature is the mandate of Heaven. Heaven's mandate encompasses origin, flourishing, benefit, and correctness—qualities subtle and endless, which we call sincerity. This mandate, bestowed upon humans, becomes the Five Constant Virtues: benevolence, righteousness, propriety, wisdom, and faith. The sage embodies these virtues purely, as Heaven itself. Yet the common learner must strive earnestly to actualize the virtue inherent in their nature. What enables this actualization is faith. It springs not from external sources, nor can it be feigned through force—it dwells already within our essential nature. We suffer only from being clouded by desire, lacking the diligence to cultivate it.

    Heaven's sincerity is the substance of the Four Virtues; in humans, it becomes the sincere heart. Benevolence is the principle of compassion, and what actualizes that compassion is faith. So too with righteousness, propriety, and wisdom—none escape this truth. If sincerity does not depart from the Four Virtues, how can faith exist apart from benevolence, righteousness, propriety, and wisdom?

    When I direct my sincere heart toward all things, nothing I do lacks truth; nothing I encounter fails to respond. Great things like Heaven and Earth, subtle things like spirits and ghosts, small things like insects—all can be moved by faith. How much more so with people! When the sincere heart within me touches the true principle within all things, they merge mysteriously without separation, swifter than shadow or echo. The Classic of Documents says, 'The utmost sincerity moves the spirits,' and the Book of Changes declares, 'Faith reaches even pigs and fish.' This speaks of the sincere heart.

    For students cultivating the self and rulers governing the realm, nothing is more urgent than this. Thus Confucius taught, 'Reverence and faith,' and 'Hold fast to loyalty and faith.' Regarding governance, he said, 'Respect your duties and act with faith.' Zengzi, Zisi, and Mencius received and transmitted these teachings, each emphasizing them in their writings. Yet after the sage's voice ceased, deception and cunning arose daily, and in the Han and Tang dynasties, few truly understood.

    Not until the Song Master Cheng declared, 'Follow the nature of things without transgression,' and 'This means acting with sincerity,' did the hidden depths of the ancients come to light. Yet he pointed not to the substance within human nature, but to its application—how the sincere heart meets and responds to things.

    I have reflected thus: Each thing has its principle; the human heart shares this universal principle, which is nothing but reality. That fire seeks the dry and water seeks the moist is the true principle of things. That water flows downward and fire flames upward is the sincere heart of humanity. To use fire, we must kindle the dry; to lead water, we must direct it to low places. Then effort succeeds and work is accomplished. This is following things without transgression.

    If someone asks me about fire, I say it is hot; about water, I say it is cold. I speak from the fullness of my sincere heart. When people grasp the fire and their hands grow warm, drink the water and their teeth grow cold, they know my words were true, not false. But should I speak insincerely, calling fire cold and water hot, people would rightly call me mad. This is what it means to act with sincerity.

    In serving sovereigns and parents, befriending companions, in all our daily movements and stillness, whenever we meet affairs and respond to things—if all springs from the sincere heart without exception, then faith becomes vast and sublime, capable of moving Heaven and Earth, stirring spirits and ghosts, gradually bringing all to pass.

    Now the Chamberlain takes this truth as his hall's name and exhorts himself thereby. Surely he understands his foundation. No wonder his conduct is meticulous and his actions accord with righteousness, earning respect from his countrymen and recognition from his sovereign. As for tracing the paths of antiquity and the accomplishments of those who applied these truths to their deeds—Master Duanmu has exhausted these matters. What more have I to add?
  footnotes:
    - The Five Constant Virtues (五常) are benevolence (仁), righteousness (義), propriety (禮), wisdom (智), and faith (信)—foundational to Confucian ethics.
    - The Four Virtues of Heaven (元亨利貞) derive from the Book of Changes, representing the cosmic principles of origin, flourishing, benefit, and correctness.
    - Master Cheng (程子) refers to Cheng Yi (1033-1107), the great Neo-Confucian philosopher whose synthesis of sincerity and principle influenced all subsequent Korean scholarship.
